description: The first boats brought domesticated animals that later became feral after escaping or being released.
notes: Feral goats are listed as 1840 in the wikipedia article, but the gov websites say 1788

description: Water buffalo were introduced first few attempts of the British to colonize the Northern Territory of Australia, and became feral after these attempts were abandoned.
Camels were introduced for construction and transport. As cameleers left and cars were introduced in the 1920s and 1930s, camels were released and became feral.
The first signs of feral cats were seen around Sydney in the 1820s. Like water buffalo before them, banteng are introduced as a meat source for colonies in the Northern Territories.

Red Foxes were introduced to the British colonies of Van Diemen's Land (as early as 1833) and the Port Phillip District and Sydney Regions of New South Wales (as early as 1845) for the purpose of the traditional English sport of fox hunting.

In 1857–1858, Alexander Buchanan, overseer for F. H. Dutton's Anlaby Estate in the Mid-North of South Australia, released a number of rabbits for hunting sport. Their population remained fairly stable until around 1866, presumed to have been kept in check by native carnivores and were protected by an Act of Parliament, but by 1867 was out of control
Donkeys were brought to Australia from 1866 for use as pack and haulage animals because they were more resistant to poisonous plants than horses.

cane toads were introduced to Australia from Hawaii in June 1935 by the Bureau of Sugar Experiment Stations, now the Sugar Research Australia, in an attempt to control the native grey-backed cane beetle (Dermolepida albohirtum) and French's beetle (Lepidiota frenchi).
